{You have 12 points and a 4-card \S suit. To find a possible 4-4 fit you bid 2\C, the Stayman convention. Partner bids 2\H.  

You have 12 points and a 4-card \S suit. To find a possible 4-4 fit you bid 2\C, the Stayman convention. Partner bids 2\H. 

You were hoping for a \S response, but so be it. You now bid 3NT, knowing partner will correct to 4\S if he was 4-4 in the Majors, or pass if he doesn't have 4 \Ss. He passes.

The contract would be 3NT played by North.

South plays 3NT.

West leads the \CK, East follows with the \CT. Do you hold up or not?

Winner List: \S = 2 : \H = 1 : \D = 4 : \C = 1 :: Total = 8

It makes no difference whether you hold up or not, (unless their \Cs are 7-2), so go ahead and take the first trick.

Either the \HQ or the \SJ <b>MIGHT</b> become your ninth trick. 

If you try either finesse and it wins you will make your contract. If you try either finesse and it loses you will be set immediately with \Cs. Each finesse is a 50% shot.

Is there anything you can do to improve your chances? 

Of course - otherwise the question wouldn't have been asked! You can combine two chances. Obviously you cannot take both finesses, but you can try to drop the \SQ in two pulls, and if she doesn't drop you still have the \H finesse to fall back on. So win the \CA, play 4 \D winners and the \S A K, then see whether you have to try the \H finesse. 

Aha - the \SQ dropped so you take your 9 tricks.

But if she hadn't, you'd still have a 50% chance in \Hs.}
[Play "W"]CK

